AB  - This study goal was to identify correlations of shrub and tree species with environmental variables, in a Deciduous Seasonal Forest in southern Brazil. Individuals in the arboreal stratum (DBH >= 5 cm) and natural regeneration (Class II: 1 <= DBH < 5 cm; Class II: DBH < 1 cm and height >= 20 cm) were sampled. Spearman's coefficient was used to determine the correlations. Some species were related to different environmental variables as the stage of development. For example, Actinostemon concolor and Sorocea bonplandii were tolerant to shallow soils, with higher levels of stoniness, a recurrent situation in the forests of the Southern Plateau edge, while Cupania vernalis and Nectandra megapotamica were correlated negatively to these variables. The zoochoric species are important for the formation of the arboreal component and the establishment of populations. The different relationships observed show that the use of shrub and tree species in ecological restoration should be based on the analysis of potentially favorable or limiting environmental variables to the establishment of these species.
