AB  - Worldwide, fungal richness peaks in tropical forest biomes where they are the primary drivers of decomposition. Understanding how environmental and anthropogenic factors influence tropical macrofungal fruiting patterns should provide insight as to how, for example, climate change and deforestation may impact their long-term demographic stability and evolutionary potential. However, in Amazonia no studies have yet to disentangle the effects of substrate, seasonality and forest history on phenology. Here, we quantitate spatial and temporal variation in community structure of fruiting macrofungi in relation to these factors at a long-term forest management research site in central Amazonia: the Biomass and Nutrients of Tropical Rain Forest (BIONTE's). Basidiome surveys of four substrate classes (leaves, soil, branches and trunks) were conducted along 250m(2) transects in primary and secondary (managed) forests, between 2012-13. From the 669 basidiomes collected, 290 taxa were identified of which 44 percent were restricted to primary and 36 percent to secondary forests. Although species-accumulation curves did not asymptote, rarefaction analyses and Fisher's alpha indicate contrasting differences in richness among forests in relation to substrate type. For example, leaf litter basidiome richness was higher in secondary forests, whereas the contrary was observed for soil communities, suggesting that variation in fruiting patterns in relation to disturbance is substrate-dependent possibly due to differences in necromass quality and/or understory micro-climates. Furthermore, secondary forests harbored significantly lower basidiome richness and abundance in dry months, suggesting synergistic impacts of seasonality and management history on fruiting regimes.
   Resumo As florestas tropicais abrigam grande diversidade de fungos, e estes por sua vez sAo responsaveis pela ciclagem de grande parte da materia organica produzida nesses biomas. Diante dessa importancia, e relevante entender como os fatores ambientais e antropogenicos influenciam o surgimento e distribuicAo dos fungos, ainda que local, por meio de informacoes de como mudancas climaticas e o desflorestamento poderiam impactar essas comunidades em longo prazo. O objetivo deste trabalho foi comparar, em escala local, a diversidade de macrofungos Agaricales em area de manejo florestal do Projeto BIONTE (Biomass and Nutrients of Tropical Rain Forest) na Amazonia Central, quando florestas primarias e secundarias (manejadas) foram utilizadas para monitorar, coletar e identificar macrofungos Agaricales, de acordo com quatro classes de substratos (folhas, solo, galhos e troncos), ao longo de transectos de 250m(2), durante o periodo de 2012-13. Como resultado, dos 669 macrofungos coletados, 290 especies/morfoespecies foram identificadas, sendo 44% restritas a floresta primaria e 36% a floresta secundaria. As curvas de acumulo de especies nAo atingiram a assimptota, porem analises de rarefacAo e alpha de Fisher indicaram diferencas entre as florestas de acordo com o substrato. No substrato folha, a riqueza de especies foi maior para a floresta secundaria, enquanto para o substrato solo, esse indice foi maior para a floresta primaria. Assim pode-se sugerir que a variacAo no padrAo de frutificacAo relacionado com o substrato pode ser devido a diferencas na qualidade de necromassa e/ ou no micro-clima dos sub-bosques. Alem disso, a floresta secundaria apresentou significantemente baixas riqueza e diversidade na estacAo seca quando comparada com a floresta primaria, sugerindo um efeito sinergico do impacto da sazonalidade e da historia de manejo dessas areas nas frutificacoes dos macrofungos.
